---
/**
 * ETF - /etf/
 * Product long-form page. Body content is the compliance-approved
 * "ETF Page Content - Shriram Financial Services V3" document, rendered
 * word-for-word through the shared design system (standardised .hero,
 * alternating sec-light / sec-tint sections, .product-page_table, .steps,
 * .cat-grid, .bullets, check-cards and FaqAccordion).
 */
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../components/site/Breadcrumb.astro';
import FaqAccordion from '../components/sections/FaqAccordion.astro';
import { faqPageSchema } from '../lib/seo';

// Got Questions? - the first 6 FAQs from the compliance doc (display cap; the
// remainder was stripped and can be restored from the doc if needed). Feeds both
// the accordion and the FAQPage JSON-LD, so markup and schema cannot drift.
const FAQS = [
  {
    q: 'What is an ETF in simple terms?',
    a: 'An ETF, also known as an Exchange-Traded Fund, is an investment fund designed to mirror an index that pools investor money into a basket of securities such as stocks, gold, or bonds, and trades on the stock exchange (NSE/BSE) in real time throughout market hours, just like a regular share.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I buy an ETF on Shriram Financial Services?',
    a: 'Open a demat account, search for ETF on the app or web platform, place a buy order at market or limit price, and units are credited on T+1.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is an ETF safe to invest in?',
    a: 'ETFs carry standard market risk tied to their underlying assets, but they are transparent, regulated by SEBI, and generally considered lower-risk than picking individual stocks due to built-in diversification.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I do a SIP in ETFs?',
    a: "Yes, through manual or scheduled recurring orders placed via your broker, since ETFs don't have a native auto-debit mandate like mutual funds.",
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the minimum investment in an ETF?',
    a: 'The minimum is the price of one ETF unit, which can range from a few hundred to a few thousand rupees depending on the specific ETF.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need a demat account to invest in ETFs?',
    a: 'Yes, a demat and trading account is mandatory since ETF units are held and traded like shares.',
  },
];

const seo = {
  title: 'ETF Investing - Exchange Funds',
  description:
    'Diversify your portfolio with ETFs tracking indices, sectors & commodities. Trade with low expense ratios via Shriram Financial Services.',
  path: '/etf',
  jsonLd: [faqPageSchema(FAQS.map((f) => ({ question: f.q, answer: f.a })))],
};
---

<BaseLayout seo={seo} mainClass="rev-rise-scale">
  <!-- ================= HERO (standardised, rule 7) ================= -->
  <section class="hero" id="sec-hero" data-section="hero">
    <Breadcrumb trail={[{ name: 'Products', href: '/products' }, { name: 'ETFs' }]} />
    <div class="hero-inner" data-enter>
      <h1>ETF in India — Trade Smarter, Invest Wiser</h1>
      <p class="lead">Invest in ETFs across equity, gold, debt, and thematic categories, with live prices, zero account-opening charges, and expert support from Shriram Financial Services. Whether you are just starting or scaling a portfolio, your ETF journey begins here.</p>
      <div class="cta"><a class="btn-gold" href="/opendemataccount">Start Investing</a></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= EXCHANGE-TRADED FUNDS: DIVERSIFIED INVESTING ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-intro" data-section="intro" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center" data-enter="2">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">Exchange-Traded Funds: Diversified Investing Made Flexible</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">Trade Exchange Traded Funds with Shriram Financial Services and get mutual fund–style diversification with the flexibility of buying and selling in real time. Choose from a curated range of equity, debt, and gold ETFs, each tradeable in real time at prices that track their underlying index closely. For investors who want diversification without the overhead of active fund selection, our ETF shelf stays transparent, liquid, and easy to enter or exit - backed by advisory support to help you pick the right ETFs for your portfolio.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h3 class="sub-title">Key terms every ETF Investor should know:</h3>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li><strong>NAV (Net Asset Value):</strong> the per-unit value of the fund's underlying assets, calculated once at the end of each trading day.</li>
        <li><strong>iNAV (Indicative NAV):</strong> a real-time estimate of an ETF's fair value, published throughout the trading session, so the market price doesn't drift too far from the underlying assets.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="sub-lead">Note: ETFs have an NAV, but unlike regular mutual funds, ETF transactions are executed at the market price rather than the NAV.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= HOW EXCHANGE-TRADED FUNDS WORK ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-tint" id="sec-how" data-section="how" style="gap:56px;align-items:center;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px;width:100%">
      <h2 class="sec-title">How Exchange-Traded Funds Work?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">An ETF maintains price efficiency and liquidity through a sophisticated 5-step creation and redemption mechanism involving Authorised Participants (APs), the AMC, and the stock exchange. This process prevents the ETF's market price from drifting far from the real value of its underlying assets.</p>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Here is how the process works, step by step:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="steps" data-reveal-row>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">1</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Authorised Participant (AP) Assembles the Basket</h4><p>The AP, typically a large financial institution or market maker, purchases a pre-defined basket of securities that exactly mirrors the ETF's target index (for example, all 50 stocks of the Nifty 50 in their exact index weights).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">2</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Units Are Created with the AMC</h4><p>The AP delivers this security basket to the Asset Management Company (AMC), which in turn issues a block of new ETF units, known as a Creation Unit, to the AP.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">3</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>ETF Units Are Listed on the Exchange</h4><p>These newly issued ETF units are listed on NSE and BSE, where retail and institutional investors can buy and sell them throughout market hours at live, exchange-quoted prices.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">4</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Investors Buy and Sell on Exchange</h4><p>An investor with a demat account purchases ETF units on the exchange through the broker (Shriram Financial Services) at the prevailing market price.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">5</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Redemption When Required</h4><p>When the AP wishes to exit, it accumulates a sufficient block of ETF units, returns them to the AMC, and gets back the underlying basket of securities. This mechanism keeps the ETF's market price aligned with its iNAV — the real-time estimated value of the underlying portfolio.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= TYPES OF ETFs AVAILABLE IN INDIA ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-types" data-section="types" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">What are the Types of ETFs Available in India?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">India's Exchange-Traded Fund market has evolved substantially since the country's first ETF. Today, investors can access seven distinct categories of ETFs on NSE and BSE, spanning asset classes, geographies, and investment strategies. Here is a definitive overview of every type of ETF available in India:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cat-grid" data-reveal-row>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Equity ETF</h4><p>Tracks a stock market index such as the Nifty 50 or Sensex, giving you exposure to a diversified basket of large, liquid companies in a single trade.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Gold &amp; Silver ETF</h4><p>Commodity-based ETFs backed by physical gold or silver held in secure vaults, letting you invest in precious metals without the storage, purity, or making-charge concerns of physical bullion.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Debt/Bond ETF</h4><p>Invests in government securities, treasury bills, or corporate bonds, offering relatively stable, income-oriented exposure to fixed income markets.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Sectoral/Thematic ETF</h4><p>Focused ETFs that provide exposure to specific sectors or investment themes such as banking, technology, infrastructure, or manufacturing.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>International ETF</h4><p>Tracks a foreign index (e.g., Nasdaq 100 or S&amp;P 500), giving Indian investors a route to global diversification through a domestic demat account.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Smart Beta ETF</h4><p>Follows rule-based strategies (such as low-volatility, momentum, or quality factors) that combine passive investing with factor-based portfolio construction, rather than simple market-cap weighting, aiming to improve risk-adjusted returns.</p></div>
      <div class="cat"><h4>Index ETF</h4><p>A broad term for any ETF that passively replicates a market index, the most common and lowest-cost category of ETF in India.</p></div>
    </div>
    <p class="sec-lead">Different ETF categories may suit different investment goals, making it important to evaluate investment objectives, risk tolerance, and time horizon before investing.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= KEY DIFFERENCES BETWEEN ETFs AND MUTUAL FUNDS ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-tint" id="sec-vs" data-section="vs" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">Key Differences Between ETFs and Mutual Funds</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Choosing between an Exchange-Traded Fund and a mutual fund depends on how much flexibility you want in your trading, your investment horizon, and your focus on minimizing costs. While both options offer diversified portfolios managed by professional AMCs, their operational setups result in different fee structures and liquidity profiles.</p>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Here's a side-by-side comparison:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t3 bordered" style="min-width:640px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>Parameters</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>ETF</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Mutual Fund</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Trading Hours</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Real-time, throughout market hours (9:15 am–3:30 pm)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">24x7</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Expense Ratio/Brokerage</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Typically 0.05%–0.50% (passive)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Typically 0.50%–2.25% (active funds)</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">SIP Availability</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Yes, available</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Yes Available</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Demat Account Needed</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Yes, mandatory</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Optional</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Taxation</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Same capital gains rules as equities/debt by category</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Same capital gains rules by category</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Liquidity</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Depends on trading volume on the exchange</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Guaranteed at NAV via the AMC</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Transparency</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Holdings visible  post settlement.(users can view unsettled/T1 Quantity as well)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Holdings  is visible post settlement</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Stock price /NAV Frequency</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Real time streaming during market hours</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Calculated once, end-of-day</p></div>
    </div></div>
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h3 class="sub-title">When to Choose an ETF:</h3>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>You have a demat account and want a smart investment.</li>
        <li>You want intraday pricing or tactical entry/exit flexibility.</li>
        <li>You are building a large passive portfolio where the expense ratio matters at scale.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h3 class="sub-title">When to Choose a Mutual Fund:</h3>
      <ul class="bullets">
        <li>You want a fully automated SIP without manual intervention.</li>
        <li>You do not have a demat account.</li>
        <li>You prefer guaranteed NAV execution without bid-ask spread risk.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= HOW TO INVEST IN ETFs ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-invest" data-section="invest" style="gap:56px;align-items:center;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px;width:100%">
      <h2 class="sec-title">How to Invest in Exchange-Traded Funds?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">Buying an ETF in India requires a demat account and a trading account with a SEBI-registered broker. Shriram Financial Services makes the entire process fully digital, via the Antara app, and completes onboarding in a few minutes.</p>
      <p class="sec-lead">Here is how to invest in ETFs with Shriram Financial Services:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="steps" data-reveal-row>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">1</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Open a demat account via Antara</h4><p>Visit the Shriram Financial Services website or download the Antara app. Complete your KYC using PAN, Aadhaar, and bank details — the process typically takes only a few minutes.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">2</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Activate your trading account</h4><p>Complete the online verification process to link your bank account and activate your real-time exchange trading access. Add investment capital to your account instantly using UPI or Net Banking,</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">3</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Search for the ETF ticker on NSE/BSE</h4><p>Search for your preferred ETF by name or ticker symbol (e.g., 'NIFTYBEES' for the Nippon Nifty 50 ETF on NSE).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">4</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Place a buy order</h4><p>Choose a market order (executes at the current price) or a limit order (executes only at your specified price), and enter the quantity.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">5</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Units are credited T+1</h4><p>Once your order is executed, ETF units are credited to your demat account on a T+1 settlement basis, in line with exchange rules.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">6</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Track your holdings via the app</h4><p>Monitor live prices, NAV, and portfolio performance anytime through the Antara Mobile app.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="width:100%">For regular investors, Shriram Financial Services supports a manual ETF SIP mechanism (predefined ETF basket), enabling you to schedule recurring purchases aligned with your investment cadence.</p>
    <a class="btn-gold" href="/opendemataccount" style="align-self:center">Start Buying ETFs</a>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= SIP IN ETFs ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-tint" id="sec-sip" data-section="sip" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">Can you do a Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) in ETFs?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Yes, you can do a SIP in Exchange-Traded Funds, but it works differently from a mutual fund SIP. In a mutual fund SIP, your bank account is debited automatically via NACH mandate, and units are allotted at end-of-day NAV. In an ETF SIP, you initiate the purchase manually (or via a broker-facilitated trigger) during market hours, at live exchange prices.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t3 bordered" style="min-width:640px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>Parameters</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>ETF SIP</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Mutual Fund SIP</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Execution Method</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Manual trigger or broker-facilitated mandate creation &amp; order execution during market hours.</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Fully automated via NACH bank mandate</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Pricing</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Live exchange price at the time of execution</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">End-of-day NAV (fixed price)</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Demat Account Needed</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Required</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Not required / Optional</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Minimum Amount</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">1 unit of ETF (price varies by ETF)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">As low as ₹100–500</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Flexibility</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Can skip, modify, or stop any month easily</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Pause/stop via the Purse+ app</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Brokerage</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Standard brokerage per trade applies</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">No brokerage; expense ratio embedded in NAV</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Rupee Cost Averaging</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Applies — buy at different prices each cycle</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Applies — buy at different NAVs each cycle</p></div>
    </div></div>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= ETF CHARGES AND EXPENSE RATIO ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-charges" data-section="charges" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">ETF Charges and Expense Ratio</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">Exchange-Traded Funds are popular largely because of their low total cost of ownership compared to actively managed mutual funds. Here's a breakdown of what you actually pay when investing in an ETF:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t4 bordered" style="min-width:760px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>Cost Component</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>What It Is</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Typical Rate (India 2025)</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Who It Goes To</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Brokerage</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Broker's fee for executing your buy/sell order on exchange</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">₹0–₹20 per order or 0.01%–0.05% (flat-fees)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Stockbroker</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Securities Transaction Tax (STT)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Government tax on equity ETF transactions</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">0.1% on delivery buy; 0.025% on intraday sell</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Government</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">GST on Brokerage</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">18% GST applied to the brokerage amount</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">18% of brokerage charged</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Government</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Depository Participant (DP) Charges</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Charge for debiting ETF units from your demat on sale</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">₹12–₹25 per scrip per day of sell (varies by DP)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">CDSL / NSDL via broker</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Impact Cost/Bid-Ask Spread</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Implicit cost due to gap between buy and sell price on exchange</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">0.01%–0.30% depending on ETF liquidity</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Market</p></div>
    </div></div>
    <p class="sec-lead">Put together, the total cost of owning a passive Nifty 50 ETF can work out to roughly 0.10%–0.30% a year, compared to 1%–2.25% for an actively managed equity mutual fund — a meaningful difference over a long investment horizon once compounding is factored in.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= HOW ARE ETF GAINS TAXED IN INDIA ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-tint" id="sec-tax" data-section="tax" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">How are ETF Gains Taxed in India?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">ETF taxation in India depends on the type of ETF and how long you hold it. Equity ETFs may qualify for equity taxation, while Gold and Debt ETFs are taxed differently. Since tax rules can vary by product and may change over time, investors should check the latest tax provisions before investing or redeeming. Here's how each major ETF category is taxed:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t4 bordered" style="min-width:760px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>ETF Type</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Tax Treatment</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Rate</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Holding Period</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Equity ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">STCG if held under 12 months; LTCG if held 12+ months</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">STCG: 20% | LTCG: 12.5% above ₹1.25L/year</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG threshold: 12 months</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Gold ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG applies after 24 months; STCG before that</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG: 12.5% (no indexation) | STCG: Income slab rate</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG threshold: 24 months</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Silver ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Same treatment as Gold ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG: 12.5% after 24 months | STCG: Slab rate</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">LTCG threshold: 24 months</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Debt / Bond ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">All gains added to total income (post-Apr 2023)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Income slab rate — regardless of holding period</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">No LTCG benefit post-Apr 2023</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">International ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Treated as debt funds for tax (post-Apr 2023 Finance Act)</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Income slab rate — regardless of holding period</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">No LTCG benefit post-Apr 2023</p></div>
    </div></div>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Note: Tax rates cited are for FY 2025-26 as per Budget 2024. Rates are subject to change. Consult a SEBI-registered tax advisor for personalised guidance.</p>
    <a class="btn-gold" href="/contactus" style="align-self:flex-start">Speak to our Advisor/RM</a>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= TOP ETFs TO CONSIDER ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-top" data-section="top" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">Top ETFs to Consider — Nifty 50, Gold, Banking &amp; More</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">Selecting the right Exchange-Traded Fund requires evaluating more than just past returns. The key parameters are the size of assets under management (AUM) (larger AUM means stronger market activity and smaller bid-ask spreads), better liquidity, expense ratio (lower is better), tracking error (closer to zero is better), and alignment with your investment objective.</p>
      <p class="sec-lead">Rather than a definitive ranking, here's a curated look at category-leading ETFs worth considering, based on AUM, cost, and trading liquidity:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t3 bordered" style="min-width:640px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>Category</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>Example ETF</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>AUM / Expense Ratio</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Nifty 50 ETF</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Tracks the Nifty 50 index</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">High AUM · Low expense ratio</p></div>
