  <!-- ================= HOW TO BUILD AN ETF PORTFOLIO ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-tint" id="sec-portfolio" data-section="portfolio" style="gap:56px;align-items:center;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px;width:100%">
      <h2 class="sec-title">How to Build an ETF Portfolio?</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary)">Building an ETF portfolio in India involves the following steps:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="steps" data-reveal-row>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">1</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Define your goal and horizon</h4><p>Are you building a retirement corpus (15+ years), saving for a child's education (10 years), or creating an emergency buffer (3–5 years)? Your goal sets your equity, debt, and gold split.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">2</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Choose your asset allocation</h4><p>Use the model approaches, shared below, as a starting point. Adjust based on your risk tolerance — higher equity for longer horizons, more debt/gold for shorter timelines.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">3</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Select ETFs within each category</h4><p>For each allocation bucket, choose the highest AUM, lowest expense ratio ETF available.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-div"></div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="num">4</div>
        <div class="st-body"><h4>Invest regularly and review annually</h4><p>Set up scheduled recurring orders for your monthly SIP amount. Review allocations once a year or after major life events, not in response to market movements.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary);width:100%">ETFs are versatile building blocks for a low-cost, diversified portfolio. Here are two model approaches, from simple to more advanced:</p>
    <div class="row-2" data-reveal-row style="width:100%">
      <div class="card">
        <h4 class="card-h">Beginner: The 3-ETF Portfolio</h4>
        <ul class="bullets">
          <li><strong>Nifty 50 ETF (60%):</strong> Core equity exposure to India's largest companies</li>
          <li><strong>Gold ETF (20%):</strong> A hedge against inflation and equity market volatility</li>
          <li><strong>Debt ETF (20%):</strong> Stability and income, reducing overall portfolio risk</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4 class="card-h">Advanced: Core-Satellite Strategy</h4>
        <ul class="bullets">
          <li><strong>Core — Nifty 50 ETF (40%):</strong> Stable, broad-market foundation of the portfolio</li>
          <li><strong>Satellite — Midcap ETF (20%):</strong> Higher growth potential from mid-sized companies</li>
          <li><strong>Satellite — International ETF (20%):</strong> Geographic diversification beyond Indian markets</li>
          <li><strong>Satellite — Gold ETF (20%):</strong> A tactical hedge and portfolio stabiliser</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary);width:100%">Regardless of which model you start with, the core principle of ETF portfolio construction is consistency over complexity: choose low-cost, high-AUM ETFs, invest regularly via a disciplined SIP cadence, and review allocations annually (or after major life events) rather than reacting to short-term market movements.</p>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="color:var(--color-text-secondary);width:100%">Note: The ETF portfolio strategies shared above are for informational purposes only, intended to help investors understand different approaches to portfolio building, and do not assure any specific outcome. Investors should evaluate their financial goals, risk appetite, and investment horizon before making any investment decision.</p>
    <a class="btn-gold" href="/opendemataccount" style="align-self:center">Build Your Portfolio</a>
  </section>

  <!-- ================= RISKS OF INVESTING IN ETFs ================= -->
  <section class="section stack sec-light" id="sec-risks" data-section="risks" style="gap:56px;justify-content:center">
    <div class="stack" style="gap:16px">
      <h2 class="sec-title">Risks of Investing in ETFs</h2>
      <p class="sec-lead">ETFs are among the most transparent and well-regulated investment products in India, but like any market-linked instrument, they carry risks that every investor must understand before committing capital. The good news - most ETF-specific risks are manageable with informed fund selection and disciplined investing behaviour.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="t-scroll"><div class="product-page_table t3 bordered" style="min-width:760px">
      <div class="cell th"><p>Risk Type</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>What It Means</p></div><div class="cell th"><p>How to Manage It</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Market Risk</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">ETF prices fall when the underlying index or asset class declines — unavoidable in any equity or commodity investment</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Invest with a long time horizon (5+ years for equity ETFs); use SIP to average costs</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Tracking Error</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">The ETF's return may deviate from its benchmark index return due to cash holdings, replication methodology, or expense drag</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Choose ETFs with consistently low tracking error (below 0.10% for index ETFs); review factsheets</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Liquidity Risk</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Low-volume ETFs may have wide bid-ask spreads, making it expensive to buy or sell at fair value</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Prefer ETFs with high AUM (above ₹500 Cr) and active daily trading volumes on NSE/BSE</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Impact Cost</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Large orders in illiquid ETFs can move the price against you, increasing your effective cost</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Use limit orders instead of market orders; avoid thinly traded sectoral ETFs for large ticket sizes</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Low AUM Risk</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">ETFs with very small AUM may be wound up by the AMC, forcing premature redemption</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Avoid ETFs with AUM below ₹100 Cr; check the AMC's ETF track record and commitment</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Delisting Risk</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Close-ended ETFs or ETFs with insufficient investor interest may be delisted from the exchange</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Invest primarily in open-ended, SEBI-compliant ETFs with diversified investor bases</p></div>
      <div class="cell tb"><p class="k">Currency Risk</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">International ETFs carry USD/INR exchange rate risk — rupee depreciation can amplify or reduce returns</p></div><div class="cell tb"><p class="v">Size international ETF allocation appropriately (10–20% of total portfolio)</p></div>
    </div></div>
    <p class="sec-lead" style="font-style:italic">Regulatory Note: Mutual fund ETFs in India are regulated by SEBI. Past performance of any ETF does not guarantee future returns. Please read the Scheme Information Document (SID) and Key Information Memorandum (KIM) before investing.</p>
  </section>

